      "text": "Goldman Sachs ActiveBeta Emerging Markets Equity ETF (GEM) Move Up 0.14% on Oct 19 \nOctober 19, 2017 - By Adrian Erickson \nShares of Goldman Sachs ActiveBeta Emerging Markets Equity ETF (NYSEARCA:GEM) last traded at 34.83, representing a move of 0.14%, or 0.05 per share, on volume of 68,752 shares. After opening the trading day at 34.81, shares of Goldman Sachs ActiveBeta Emerging Markets Equity ETF traded in a close range. Goldman Sachs ActiveBeta Emerging Markets Equity ETF currently has a total float of shares and on average sees shares exchange hands each day. The stock now has a 52-week low of 26.01 and high of 35.11. The Italian Equity Market \nThe European economy is immensely growing and Italy is one of the many reasons behind such success. The companies that work at its markets as Goldman Sachs ActiveBeta Emerging Markets Equity ETF prefer to stay there as long as possible. \nItaly cannot be underestimated when it comes to corporate governance. Its capacities as a nation go beyond the tourism front. The blooming Italian equity market is a sure testament to that. \nThe Italian economy might just be one of the best contributors to the growth of the European economy. It is because of countries like Italy that Europe had become the enormous regional success that it is known today. It gives more possibilities to the Goldman Sachs ActiveBeta Emerging Markets Equity ETF stocks. Borsa Italiana/Italia Borsa/Piazza Affari \nThe Borsa Italiana is the primary stock exchange in Italy that is based at the Palazzo Mezzanotte in Milan. It had been established in February 1808 by Eugène de Beauharnais, Napoleonic Kingdom of Italy Viceroy— making it one of the oldest stock exchanges in the world. Like most stock exchanges, the Borsa Italiana had initially been a public entity. It had not been privatized until 1998. \nIn 2007, the Borsa Italiana had been acquired in an all-stock transaction by London Stock Exchange Group, leading to its merger with the London Stock Exchange. \nPresently, more than 300 companies are listed on the Borsa Italiana, bringing its total market capitalization to about $645 billion. \nThe pre-market session on the Borsa Italiana begins at 8:00 a.m. and concludes at 9:00 a.m.; the regular session begins at 9:00 a.m. and concludes at 5:30 p.m.; and the post-market session begins at 6:00 p.m. and concludes at 8:30 p.m. The Borsa Italiana has one of the longest trading hours in the world. This gives domestic and international investors alike the opportunity to trade on it with enough time. And Goldman Sachs ActiveBeta Emerging Markets Equity ETF to receive an attention from these investors. FTSE Milano Italia Borsa (MIB) \nThe FTSE MIB is the benchmark index in Italy. It is a free-float market-capitalization-weighted index that measures the 40 biggest companies listed on the Borsa Italiana. It had replaced the MIB30, which measures the 30 biggest companies listed on the Borsa Italiana, in September 2004. \nThe FTSE MIB i formerly known as the S&P/MIB because the S&P operated it until June 2009 when the FTSE had taken over. \nRepresenting roughly 80% of the total market capitalization on the Borsa Italiana, the FTSE MIB is a powerful indicator of the Italian economy’s situation. It is quarterly rebalanced to make sure that the components provide a clearer indication of the trade and commerce environment in Italy. \nThe FTSE MIB holds an all-time high of 50,108.56, which had last been seen in March 2000; and an all-time low of 12,362.50, which had last been seen in July 2012 after the Spanish debt dilemma rippled adversaries throughout Europe. \nItaly is an ideal place to invest in, especially for those who are seeking meaningful returns. They can also check validity of Goldman Sachs ActiveBeta Emerging Markets Equity ETF. With it serving as one the nations in Europe with compelling economies, investors are highly recommended to trade on the Borsa Italiana as a way of betting on Italy’s economic growth prospects. \nMore notable recent Goldman Sachs ActiveBeta Emerging Markets Equity ETF (NYSEARCA:GEM) news were published by: Marketwatch.com which released: “Goldman Sachs ActiveBeta Emerging Markets Equity ETF” on September 28, 2015, also Etftrends.com with their article: “The $2.5 Billion Success of Goldman Sachs’ Active Beta ETFs” published on December 09, 2016, Etftrends.com published: “USAA Potential ETF Debut Puts a Dent in Goldman’s Plans” on August 31, 2017. More interesting news about Goldman Sachs ActiveBeta Emerging Markets Equity ETF (NYSEARCA:GEM) were released by: Nasdaq.com and their article: “A Closer Look At The New Goldman Sachs ETFs” published on October 13, 2015 as well as Barrons.com‘s news article titled: “Goldman Sachs Assigns Ticker Symbols, Fund Managers for Forthcoming ETFs” with publication date: May 05, 2015. Receive News & Ratings Via Email - Enter your email address below to receive a concise daily summary of the latest news and analysts' ratings with our daily email newsletter. Free Email Newsletter Enter your email address below to get the latest news and analysts' ratings for your stocks with our free daily email newsletter: Recent Posts",
